Data Analytics: Lebanese Disaster Relief Data¶

As a result of the August 4 explosion, the ongoing economic crisis, and the coronavirus pandemic, the Lebanese people are facing one of the most difficult living conditions in years. Relief efforts are being organized globally to help mitigate the burden on the Lebanese population and Lebanese citizens. The dataset we will study below contains information on communities in lebanon regarding their living conditions, medical and psychological health, and needs. Data was recorded by non-profits in Beirut and surrounding areas and the following report contains the documentation of the data cleaning.

The dataset contains 93 different variables, and 32,079 data entries. So, over 32,000 households were interviewed, with 93 questions each. Variables were numbered (from 1 to 93) for ease

Defining Helpful Functions¶

Inspect(col)¶

Outputs the type and percentage of missing values in each column.

  • For numericla columns (float64 or int64), it outputs the range, distribution of values
  • For ordinal/ categorical columns, it outputs unique values
In [ ]:
def inspect(var: str):
  if df[var].dtypes == "O":
    print("------------------------------PRINT ALL AND TYPE-----------------------------------")
    #print(df[var])
    print("-------------------------------UNIQUE VALUES---------------------------------------")
    print(df[var].unique())
    print("---------------------------NUMBER OF UNIQUE VALUES---------------------------------")
    print(len(df[var].unique()))
    print("-------------------------NUMBER OF MISSING VALUES----------------------------------")
    print(df[var].isna().sum())
    print("-------------------------PERCENT OF MISSING VALUES---------------------------------")
    print(df[var].isna().sum()/len(df[var]))
    print("-------------------------DISTRIBUTION OF VALUES---------------------------------")
    df[var].value_counts(normalize=True).plot.barh()
    plt.show()   
  elif df[var].dtypes == "float64" or df[var].dtypes == "int64" :
    print("------------------------------PRINT ALL AND TYPE-----------------------------------")
    #print(df[var])
    print("-------------------------------RANGE OF VALUES---------------------------------------")
    print("MIN", df[var].min())
    print("MAX", df[var].max())
    #Plot the distribution
    print("-------------------------NUMBER OF MISSING VALUES----------------------------------")
    print(df[var].isna().sum())
    print("-------------------------PERCENT OF MISSING VALUES---------------------------------")
    print(df[var].isna().sum()/len(df[var]))
    print("-------------------------DISTRIBUTION OF VALUES---------------------------------")
    hist = df[var].hist(bins=15, alpha=0.5)
    plt.title(var + " Distribution")
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')

replaceWordSet(mistakenWords: set[str],replacement: str)¶

Replaces all the words in the mistakenWords set with the replacement string.

In [ ]:
def replaceWordSet(df, col, mistakenWords, replacement):
  uniqueVals = list(pd.unique(df[col]))
  for i in uniqueVals:
    if i in mistakenWords:
      df[col]= df[col].replace(i, replacement)
  return df[col]

toLowerCase(df: pandas.Dataframe, col: str)¶

Replaces the values of the column named col with their lowercase string equivalent.

In [ ]:
def toLowerCase(df, col:str):
  uniqueVals = list(pd.unique(df[col]))
  for i in uniqueVals:
    if not pd.isnull(i):
      df[col]= df[col].replace(str(i), str(i).lower())
  return df[col]

scoreOptions(keywords: List[str], lookupTable: Dict[str, int])¶

Replaces each value in column named col with the sum of the scores of different comma and underscode separated values, each keyword's score is provided in the lookupTable dictionary.

In [ ]:
def compute_score(keywords, lookupTable):
  score = 0
  for keyword in keywords:
    if lookupTable.get(keyword):
      score+=lookupTable.get(keyword)
  return score
def scoreOptions(df, col, lookupTable: Dict[str, int]):
  column = list(df[col])
  #Compute total score from set of keywords in the column example: (glass, frames)
  split_by_comma_then_underscore = lambda string:set([entry for term in string.split(",") for entry in term.split("_") ]) if not pd.isnull(string) else string
  column = map(split_by_comma_then_underscore, column)
  scores = [keywords if pd.isnull(keywords) else compute_score(keywords, lookupTable)  for keywords in column]
  df[col] = scores
  return df[col]

def select_options(col):
  for index, row in df.iterrows():
    if (type(row[col])!= float):
      row[col] = row[col].split(",")
